      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Church Next Door</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from ACLU president Nadine Strossen disputes Marci A Hamilton's July 14 Op-Ed article on Congressional proposal to protect religious freedoms (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''When Churches Are Neighbors'' (Op-Ed, July 14), Marci A. Hamilton asserts that a Congressional proposal to protect religious freedom contravenes the First Amendment's establishment clause, which prohibits government favoritism toward religion. If this were so, the legislation would not be supported by the American Civil Liberties Union.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''When Churches Are Neighbors'' (Op-Ed, July 14), Marci A. Hamilton asserts that a Congressional proposal to protect religious freedom contravenes the First Amendment's establishment clause, which prohibits government favoritism toward religion. If this were so, the legislation would not be supported by the American Civil Liberties Union.</p>
        <p>In a controversial 1990 decision, the Supreme Court gutted the free exercise clause of the First Amendment. Since then, religious institutions have been subject to unprecedented government interference, including the use of zoning laws. Communities have barred worship services in private homes and excluded houses of worship.</p>
        <p>The modest bill that Ms. Hamilton opposes would merely restore some rights that religious groups enjoyed until 1990. Far from allowing these groups to be bad neighbors, the law would simply allow them to be in the neighborhood.</p>
        <p>NADINE STROSSEN  President  American Civil Liberties Union  Washington, July 15, 2000</p>
      </block>
